Pixellot camera system for online viewing
Genesee has the Pixellot camera system for online viewing of Genesee home games. Fans are able to access viewing through the NFHS network. Please follow these steps to set up an account and pay for a subscription. Some of our league schools have the cameras and more are working on it.
Here's how to watch:
1) Visit www.NFHSnetwork.com and sign up for an account. Select the subscription you want to purchase and enter credit card information for payment.
2) Search for (Genesee High School, Genesee ID) and go to our page. Make Genesee your home team to follow.
3) Click on the event you want to watch.
4) If you want to watch on your phone, download the NFHS Network app and select Genesee High School Idaho as your school.

We are working on preparing classrooms and gearing up for students to return. Having accurate enrollments are very helpful for us in preparing for the new school year. If you are new to the school district and have not contacted the school office, please do so as soon as possible.

If your student(s) were enrolled last year and will not be attending this year please let us know.

Thank you!

Carly Stutzman

(208)285-1162

Idaho teacher-led lessons will air on IPTV Tuesday through Thursday between the hours of 8AM and Noon. Lesson replays, teacher support, and additional content will be offered online through IDLA.

To gain free access to fun summer activities related to Classroom Idaho Bootcamp broadcasts and the support of an Idaho certified teacher text "register" to 201-474-3831 or register online at https://idahoptv.idiglearning.net.

post_text:
The Idaho High School Activities Association is pleased to announce the 2019-2020 winners of the "Schools of Excellence" program, sponsored by the Idaho Army National Guard.

Genesee Highschool received 2nd place in the 1A Div 1 category.

Schools earn points based on their student-athletes’ performance in athletics, academics and sportsmanship is the top award for the IHSAA and its member schools. Way to go Bulldogs!

In addition to the primary awards, schools that score 90% on the Citizenship Component and have no player/coach ejections throughout the year or incidents of unsportsmanlike school behavior at state tournaments will receive an "Award of Excellence" certificate. The 2019-2020 Award of Excellence schools are Eagle, Timberline, Highland, Meridian, Bishop Kelly, Wood River, Ridgevue, Vallivue, Sugar-Salem, Filer, McCall-Donnelly, St. Maries, Ririe, Salmon, West Jefferson, and Genesee.

Graduation will be at 11am on June 13th. All guests must have a ticket to attend the graduation ceremony (to be distributed by the graduate’s family). This is in order for us to meet the guidelines set forth by the local health Department and the State of Idaho. No one will be allowed without a ticket.

There will be an opportunity for everyone to congratulate graduates at 1pm at the Football field. All graduates will be at the football field following the ceremony. Community members and guests will be able to say congratulations and drop off cards, gifts etc. as they go by each graduate. We hope you are able to attend this event.

Wendy J. Moore, PhD.

Superintendent
Genesee Joint School District No. 282

The Idaho State Board of Education voted on Monday 4/6 to continue "soft closure" for public schools for the remainder of the academic year ( according to district's school calendar). The State Board of Education will be looking at developing protocols for those districts who wish to attempt to reopen if possible at a later date.

What does this mean for Genesee students? Genesee Schools will be following the "soft closure" recommendation for the remainder of the school year. Teachers will continue to provide online/ packet educational services to all students through the end of May. Food Services will be provided through the first week of June.

We will be sending a letter via email out to parents today with additional details. We will continue to update you with other updates as they become available.

Thank you for your continued support.
Dr. Moore

Genesee School District will be closed through Monday, April 20th.

As of Mon., March 23 the State Board of Education has directed all districts implement a "soft closure" through Monday, April 20th. During this "soft closure" Genesee School district will follow national CDC guidelines pertaining to gatherings and social distancing. While students are not permitted in schools, we will continue facilitating essential services such as food services, online instruction and support. Parents and guardians will be receiving an email today outlining district procedures and services that are set to begin on April 6th.

Thank you for your support. We will continue to provide updates as information becomes available and necessary.

Sincerely,
Dr. Wendy Moore, Superintendent

post_text:
Genesee Schools will be closed, Monday March 2nd for cleaning.

As part of Jazz Fest tradition Genesee Schools has allowed Jackson Highschool from WA to stay in our building to help defray their transportation costs.

Saturday a.m. administration was notified that Jackson High had a student ill with the coronavirus.

The student who is ill WAS NOT part of the group who stayed in our building. The Health Department has also assured us that the students who did stay in our building were not in contact with the student who was ill.

However, as a precautionary measure for our own students and staff we are cancelling all classes and activities Monday, March 2nd. The district will use this time to clean and sanitize the building.

We apologize for the inconvenience but we want to do everything we can to ensure student and staff safety.

School will resume on Tuesday, March 3rd at 8:00 a.m.

Dr. Wendy Moore, Supt.

post_text:
Junior Girls:

Your American Legion Auxiliary of Genesee is seeking a representative to attend Girls State, a week-long intensive training that teaches young women responsible citizenship. This training program teaches participants how to be informed and engaged citizens, how to explore issues and interests, and how to participate in meetings using parliamentary procedure. The 2020 Idaho Syringa Girls State Session will be held June 14-19, 2020, at Northwest Nazarene University in Nampa, Idaho.

To be eligible, you must complete your Junior year of high school this June, have at least one more semester of high school remaining, hold a GPA of 2.0 or higher for your Sophomore year and first semester of their Junior year. If you are interested, please email Wendy Woods at wwoods.id@gmail.com by Friday, March 6th for the next step in the process.

post_text:
Genesee PTO will be hosting a Scholastic Book Fair next week in the Multi-Purpose Room. All funds generated go towards books for sharing tree and fulfilling classroom wish lists.

Monday- Preview day, students get an opportunity to visit the fair and make a wish list! No sales until after school.

Tuesday- Books and Breakfast, Genesee Preschool-6th Grade Students and Families. Start your day with a little breakfast and a good book! 7:15 in the library.

Wednesday- Make a donation to the “All for Books” sharing tree fund, pull a taffy from the bin, if it's a winner you can choose a poster!

Thursday- Book fair BINGO! 6:00-8:00 in the MPR.

Friday- ( No school) Grand Story time from 9-noon in the MPR. Drop in for some snacks, a good story, and your last opportunity to shop the fair.

post_text:
Have you hugged your child today.....Research shows that hugging is extremely effective at healing sickness, disease, loneliness, depression, anxiety and stress.

Research shows a proper deep hug, where the hearts are pressing together, can benefit you in these ways: 1. The nurturing touch of a hug builds trust and a sense of safety.

2. Hugs can instantly boost oxytocin levels, which heal feelings of loneliness, isolation, and anger.

3. Holding a hug for an extended time lifts serotonin levels, elevating mood, creating happiness.

4. Hugs strengthen the immune system. The gentle pressure on the sternum and the emotional charge this creates activates the Solar Plexus Chakra. This stimulates the thymus gland, which regulates and balances the body's production of white blood cells, which keep you healthy and disease free.

5. Hugging boosts self-esteem. From the time we're born our family's touch shows us that we're loved and special. Hugs, therefore, connect us to our ability to self love.
